Because the recursion is a third-order polynomial, I finished off my brute force and checked $\phi$ and $\frac{1}{2}(\sqrt3-1)$ and they worked, but I can't prove you got all of the solutions.</think> <answer> There are infinitely many $\alpha$ such that $A^3 - 3A^2 + 3 = \alpha$, so after taking the cube root we can rearrange to get $\omega^2-\omega+3=a_0$. Also, $a_3 = a_0^3 - 3a_0^2 + 3$, so $a_2$ must be a root of the polynomial $a^3-3a^2+3=a_0$, so in particular it must have the same splitting field[1]. The splitting field is
\begin{align*}(a_0) &=\text{splitting field}\;\F_p[\sqrt{b-3}/p] \\
&= \text{splitting field}\;\F_p[\omega], \text{where $\omega$ is a root of $x^2-x+3$}
\end{align*}
where $p$ depends on the field. So in any case this argument works for all $a_0 = \alpha(c)$ where $\alpha\in\{\phi, \frac{1}{2}(\sqrt3-1)\}$ and $c$ is any root of $x^3-3x^2+3-\alpha$[2]. As for the actual roots of $x^2-x+3$ and $a_0=\alpha(c)$, I'm not so sure. I know the quadratic formula so far. 
</answer>

